</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Cost Factors</p>
    <h2>What affects fireplace repair cost in Los Angeles</h2>
    <div class="factors-grid">
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128293;</div><h3>Thermopile vs. gas valve &mdash; diagnose correctly</h3><p>A low-output thermopile makes the gas valve appear failed when the valve is actually fine. We test thermopile millivolt output before recommending a valve replacement. A thermopile costs $30&ndash;$80; a gas valve costs $150&ndash;$400. Getting the diagnosis right matters.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127774;</div><h3>Coastal salt air corrosion</h3><p>Malibu, Pacific Palisades, Manhattan Beach, and Venice properties within 5 miles of the ocean see accelerated corrosion on igniter wires, burner ports, and valve assemblies. We assess outdoor and coastal indoor units for corrosion and advise on extended maintenance.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128027;</div><h3>Spider / insect nests in burners</h3><p>LA fireplaces unused over summer are a common entry point for spiders, wasps, and insects that build nests in burner orifices and gas tubing. Burner cleaning is often the only fix needed &mdash; no replacement part. Flat-rate pricing charges the same as a valve replacement.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127991;</div><h3>Brand and fireplace type</h3><p>Standard gas inserts (SL, ProCom, Empire) have widely available thermopile and igniter components. Valor, Napoleon, and Regency premium systems use proprietary assemblies at higher parts pricing. Quoted separately so you see the real cost.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#127968;</div><h3>Indoor vs. outdoor access</h3><p>Indoor gas fireplace inserts sometimes require partial removal for access to gas components. Outdoor fire pits with stone or tile surrounds may require removing decorative elements. We advise on access complexity before starting.</p></div>
      <div class="factor-card"><div class="factor-icon">&#128204;</div><h3>Post-repair gas leak test</h3><p>Every gas fireplace repair that involves gas components ends with a leak test. This is not an add-on &mdash; it&rsquo;s standard on every call. We don&rsquo;t leave until the unit has been confirmed safe.</p></div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-black">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="sl">Repair vs. Replace</p>
    <h2>When to repair a fireplace, when to replace it</h2>
    <p class="lead">Gas fireplaces are almost always worth repairing &mdash; replacement involves major construction. Electric units depend on the failure.</p>
    <div class="rvr-grid">
      <div class="rvr-card repair">
        <h3>Repair makes sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Thermopile, thermocouple, or igniter failure</li>
          <li>Burner cleaning resolves the issue (no parts)</li>
          <li>Remote receiver or switch failure</li>
          <li>Built-in gas insert &mdash; replacement requires construction</li>
          <li>Total repair under 40% of replacement + installation cost</li>
          <li>Outdoor fire pit &mdash; replacement involves hardscape work</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="rvr-card replace">
        <h3>Replace makes more sense when:</h3>
        <ul class="rvr-list">
          <li>Gas valve failed on a 15+ year old unit</li>
          <li>Firebox or heat exchanger structurally compromised</li>
          <li>Budget electric unit with major component failure</li>
          <li>Outdoor unit with severe coastal corrosion throughout</li>
          <li>Parts discontinued with no reliable ETA</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

